<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Carlton's Stock-Price Plunge Reflects
   Fall From Grace of U.K. Video Highflier
   ----
   By Craig Forman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   CCTVY
</CO>
<IN>
HOME ELECTRONICS, FURNISHINGS, APPLIANCES (HMF)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- Nothing has better symbolized Britain's
rekindled entrepreneurial energy in recent times than Carlton
Communications PLC.
   Now, Carlton is facing its own energy crisis, as
yesterday's tumble in its stock price showed.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A rapid-fire series of acquisitions -- capped by its
purchases of Technicolor Holdings Inc. from Ronald Perelman
in 1988 and UEI PLC last year for $1.5 billion -- has made
the once-tiny London television-production company a major
force in the world video market. It duplicates more
videotapes than anyone else. Its high-tech graphics machines
set industry standards. Its Zenith unit, 49%-owned by
Paramount Communications Inc., makes TV programs with such
stars as Michelle Pfeiffer and Tina Turner seen in 30
countries.
   Led by its chairman and chief executive officer, Michael
Green, Carlton's pretax profits have risen nearly tenfold in
five years. And at its height last year, the company's #1.7
billion ($2.79 billion) market capitalization exceeded
Saatchi &amp; Saatchi PLC, a previous highflier whose founders
are friends of Mr. Green.
   But suddenly, like Saatchi, Carlton appears to have lost
its hustle. A vague warning from Mr. Green of slower profits
growth this fiscal year, ending Sept. 30, has contributed to
a big fall in the company's share price. On the London Stock
Exchange, Carlton dropped 43 pence a share yesterday to close
at 481 pence, off about 49% from last year's highs. American
depositary receipts, in national over-the-counter trading,
plunged $1.75 a share to close at $15.125.
   Now, holders fear the stock may tread water until June,
when the company posts first-half results, and beyond. The
performance raises some discomforting questions about
Carlton's operations and strategy. There are even whispers
that unless it pulls out of the slump, the much-feared
acquirer could one day be a target itself.
   Acquisitive Carlton's price-earnings ratio -- whose lofty
heights allowed the company to finance acquisitions through
share issues -- now has plunged to below the U.K. average.
That hampers Carlton's ability to finance acquisitions by
issuing shares, and is a setback to Mr. Green's aims to make
Carlton big enough to compete against such rivals as Sony
Corp. Carlton has recently been courting the U.K.'s Thames
Television, which it tried to buy in 1985.
   Carlton "has very much fallen from grace," says Robert
Elliot, fund manager at #6 billion Scottish Amicable
Investment Managers in Glasgow, Scotland. "It is reasonable
to assume we will not see it back on a premium, at least not
this side of a bull market."
   Carlton is the latest casualty of the curious British
fondness for boom-and-bust stories. In the past, the London
market has propelled companies such as Saatchi and Sir
Terence Conran's Storehouse PLC retailing group to
exaggerated heights, only to knock them to equally stunning
lows when bad news surfaces. Now it seems to be Carlton's
turn.
   Carlton's share-price gyrations reflect both current
problems and its transition from growth stock to
conglomerate. Mr. Perelman sold Technicolor at the right
time; tough competition is cutting margins at the unit, which
may account for over a third of Carlton's profits. (Carlton
doesn't disclose figures.) Moreover, high inflation and
interest rates are hurting the advertising market in Britain,
a country Carlton depends on for 36% of revenue.
   By branching out from its base in the back rooms of
television, Carlton is embarking on a riskier strategy to
become a media colossus with operations in hardware,
programming and broadcasting itself. The jury is out on
whether Mr. Green, 42 years old, will be as successful a
manager as he has been a deal-maker. The question is whether
he can make varied businesses work.
   Mr. Green declined to comment for this article. But he
told Carlton shareholders two weeks ago that first-quarter
revenue and pretax profits "show a respectable increase" from
a year earlier, in contrast to the "healthy" increase in
previous years. Holders who have spoken to him since say he
expects profits to grow faster next year after this year's
pause.
   Several holders say they are angry that Carlton failed to
provide earlier clues about the apparent slowdown. They
remain confused about how long the situation will last. Their
biggest fear is the apparent slowdown in the company's energy
may become permanent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900419-0157
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900419-0157.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Dayton Hudson Said to be Front-Runner
   To Buy B.A.T's Marshall Field's Chain
   ----
   By Jeffrey A. Trachtenberg
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   DH BTI
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Dayton Hudson Corp. has emerged as the clear
front-runner to acquire the Marshall Field's department store
chain, according to people familiar with the situation.
   Marshall Field's, one of the country's most famous
retailers, was put up for sale last year by B.A.T Industries
PLC as part of a restructuring to fight a takeover bid by Sir
James Goldsmith. B.A.T, which also is selling its Saks Fifth
Avenue unit, had set last Monday as the deadline for bids for
the 24-store Field's chain.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   People familiar with B.A.T, a British company that also is
involved in tobacco and financial services, said an agreement
with Dayton Hudson could be reached this week. A deal would
link two of the Midwest's largest retailers and give Dayton
Hudson dominant positions in Chicago and several other
Midwestern cities.
   Executives of Dayton Hudson and their investment bankers
from Salomon Brothers Inc. met yesterday with B.A.T
representatives to negotiate a contract, people familiar with
the talks said. The negotiations were held at the offices
here of Chadbourne &amp; Parke, the law firm representing B.A.T.
   Jerome C. Katz, a partner with Chadbourne &amp; Parke,
declined to comment. A spokesman for Minneapolis-based Dayton
Hudson also declined to comment.
   Details of the Dayton Hudson bid couldn't be learned. Some
have estimated that Marshall Field's might bring between $850
million and $950 million. Other interested parties were said
to include May Department Stores Co., based in St. Louis, and
Dillard Department Stores Inc., based in Little Rock, Ark.
   Philip Miller, chairman and chief executive officer of
Marshall Field's, said in an interview yesterday that a
management group also submitted a bid for Field's. "We
haven't had a response yet," said Mr. Miller, who declined to
comment on any other aspects of the sale.
   Marshall Field's operates l5 stores in Chicago, four in
Wisconsin, four in Texas, and one in Ohio. For the year ended
Jan. 31, 1989, the chain generated about $1.09 billion in
revenue and earned $91 million before depreciation, interest
and taxes.
   Dayton Hudson, which last year earned $410 million on
$13.64 billion in revenue, operates 37 department stores
under the Hudson and Dayton's names in Indiana, Michigan,
Ohio, Minnesota, North Dakota, South Dakota and Wisconsin.
   "It appears to be a terrific fit," said one retail
executive who declined to be identified. "Both are high-end
department stores. They share the same customer base and
dominate their key cities. What this means is that Dayton
Hudson will dominate Detroit, Chicago and Minneapolis."
   Dayton Hudson has performed extremely well in recent
years, according to some retail observers. "Basically,
they've improved the operations in all of their divisions,"
said Marcia Raley, an analyst with Dain Bosworth Inc., based
in Minneapolis. "They've also changed their promotional
stance," continued Ms. Raley. "Customers no longer think
everything is on sale. This helps gross margins because more
of their revenues are coming at full price."
   Richard Pyle, an analyst with Piper Jaffray &amp; Hopwood in
Minneapolis, said the department store division now accounts
for about 12% of Dayton Hudson's total revenue.
   "Those stores dominate their market areas," said Mr. Pyle.
"Both Dayton's in Minneapolis-St. Paul and the Hudson group
in Detroit are both probably in the 40% market-share area.
These are full-line department stores which serve a lot of
loyal customers. Marshall Field's would be an excellent
acquisition because it shares many of the same
characteristics."
   Under Mr. Miller, who took over the chief executive's job
in 1983, Marshall Field's has accomplished a substantial
turnaround. "It's a store which has successfully switched its
approach from serving the carriage trade to serving the
contemporary fashion needs of middle to upper-income
customers," said Kurt Barnard, publisher of Barnard's Retail
Marketing Report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
