<HL>
   AT&amp;T Net Rose
   12%, Sales 2.7%
   In 1st Quarter
   ---
   Long-Distance Operations,
   Slimmer Costs Cited;
   Network Failure Hurts
   ----
   By John J. Keller
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   T
</CO>
<IN>
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
EARNINGS (ERN)
COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)
</IN>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., buoyed
by continued strength in its long-distance business and
slimmer costs, said net income rose 12% in the quarter on a
2.7% increase in sales.
   Net income for the first three months was $668 million, or
62 cents a share, from $594 million, or 55 cents a share, a
year earlier. Revenue rose to $8.89 billion from $8.66
billion in the 1989 quarter.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   While earnings were slightly below analysts' expectations
of 68 cents to 70 cents a share, AT&amp;T posted a strong 21%
increase in operating profit in the quarter, to $1.18 billion
from $977 million the previous year, indicating that its
struggle to control costs is paying off.
   Net income was hurt by several factors including increased
interest expenses, a higher tax rate and costs associated
with last January's network disaster, when a software problem
shut down the company's nationwide long-distance network for
nine hours. In addition, AT&amp;T's telecommunications-equipment
business continues to suffer from increased price competition
and a softening of orders for switching equipment from local
telephone companies.
   Despite these problems, AT&amp;T Chairman Robert E. Allen said
the New York-based company's results showed it was off to "a
strong start toward making 1990 an even stronger year than
1989, which was our best."
   Mr. Allen, who made his comments at the company's annual
meeting at the convention center here, added that AT&amp;T has
set a goal for itself of increasing its earnings by at least
10% to 12% annually. "We were clearly ahead of that in the
first quarter. Typically, the first quarter is a weak one for
us." (Profit in the first quarter actually rose slightly more
than 12%.)
   However, AT&amp;T received a boost from businesses that had
not been a part of the company a year earlier, including
Istel Group Ltd., a U.K. information services company
acquired in the fourth quarter of 1989, and two divisions of
PacifiCorp Financial Services, which were purchased by AT&amp;T
Capital Corp. during the first quarter.
   AT&amp;T's revenue from product sales, including telephone and
computer equipment, increased a meager 1.2% to $2.72 billion
from $2.69 billion the year before. Mr. Allen blamed the
lackluster sales on the "rather weak economy" and a backlog
in computer-systems sales "due to customer demand and our
inability to fill that demand." To improve shipments, AT&amp;T
recently began manufacturing personal computers to augment
supplies from Intel Corp.
   Mr. Allen said the company is banking on new products to
boost sales. These include its recently announced credit
card, in which orders so far "have exceeded our wildest
expectations . . . customers are calling us by the tens of
thousands." In addition, he announced that AT&amp;T will begin
selling switching equipment based on an optical computer
processor developed by Bell Laboratories, within five years.
   Analysts reacted favorably to the company's results. "The
earnings masked what was probably AT&amp;T's best quarter since
divestiture," said Jack B. Grubman, an analyst at PaineWebber
Inc. Long-distance "volume is up 7% and operating margins
were 13.2%, two points higher than a year ago. That's a lot
of expansion for a company this size." He estimated that the
network outage alone cost AT&amp;T about three cents a share
because of lost revenue and remittances to business customers
covered under AT&amp;T's 800 Assurance Plan.
   Robert B. Morris III, telecommunications analyst at
Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co., said AT&amp;T earnings were about three
cents less than his estimate. And sales, general and
administrative expenses were 35.2% of revenue "when I had
expected 34%." But Mr. Morris said, "I wouldn't characterize
this as a disappointing quarter."
   At the shareholder meeting, Mr. Allen defended the
company's previously reported decision to withdraw its
funding of the Planned Parenthood Federation of America. AT&amp;T
announced the move on March 26 following pressure applied on
the company by shareholding anti-abortion activists.
   Referring to protests by Planned Parenthood, Mr. Allen
said: "I'm disappointed in their actions. If someone were
supporting me for 25 years, I would say `thank you.' In the
last 25 years, we funded them to the tune of $600,000, and we
never heard a word of thanks from them."
   Mr. Allen added that AT&amp;T will spend $2.5 million this
year supporting teen-pregnancy prevention programs similar to
those they had been supporting at Planned Parenthood.
   Mr. Allen said Planned Parenthood has elevated the
abortion issue to political advocacy and that "this caused
our opponents and proponents to say that we are supporting
abortion. I concluded -- I should say the {AT&amp;T} foundation
concluded -- that abortion or opposing abortion shouldn't be
supported by the corporation."
   A first-time shareholder proposal that AT&amp;T stop funding
organizations that advocate abortion managed to win 5.5% of
the votes cast at the company's annual meeting, insuring its
inclusion on the ballot for a second time at AT&amp;T's 1991
meeting. Another resolution, calling on AT&amp;T to drop its
affirmative action program, garnered 8.8% of the vote, less
than the 10% it needed to be included for the fourth time
next year.
   AT&amp;T common stock fell $1 yesterday to close at $41 a
share in New York Stock Exchange composite trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900419-0135
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900419-0135.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Rising College Costs a Sign of Success
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<LP>
   Your March 12 editorial "College Prices" bemoans college
tuition-rate increases, accuses U.S. colleges of significant
waste and exhorts them to pay attention to the forces of the
market. The editorial misleads on all counts. First, the
forces of the marketplace tell colleges that, if anything,
tuition should be rising more rapidly than it is. Rates of
return on college education have skyrocketed in recent years.
Students may pay more, but they are getting back even more in
higher income. Changes in the U.S. industrial structure away
from heavy manufacturing toward services, "inter alia", has
generated a shortage of high-paying blue-collar jobs and a
surplus of jobs requiring more-sophisticated analytical
skills. In 1973, the median income of a 30-year-old male
highschool graduate was 15% less than the income of a
30-year-old male college graduate. By 1987, the gap had
widened to 50%. College education, then, is one of the best
investments an 18-year-old can make. This, of course, is a
major reason why the share of college enrollments among the
relevant age cohort rose throughout the past decade despite
the tuition increases.
   Second, you suggest that professors' lives are too cozy.
You miss the point when you observe that professors at some
schools teach eight to 12 hours a week in the classroom.
Would we judge the work of a CEO by hours spent in the board
room? In addition to classroom hours, professors spend long
hours working with individual students, preparing for
lectures and seminars, attending meetings and doing research.
The average workweek is well over 40 hours. This is not to
say that certain professors don't take advantage of the
luxury of tenure. They do, and this is just as troubling to
those of us in academia as to the outside critics, but this
group is a small minority and surely has its analogues
elsewhere in society. It is difficult to understand how you
can believe that as a group professors are overpaid when
individuals in the private sector with similar levels of
skill and educational attainment receive salaries many times
higher. President Bush, to his credit, has noted the
problematic state of U.S. schools and the absolute necessity
of upgrading and enriching the entire educational system.
This can happen only if teacher salaries, at all levels, go
up appreciably and quickly.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   There remains the issue of making a college education
accessible to all income groups. Here the best solution is
simple. Rather than tinkering with the price of output as the
Justice Department investigation encourages (as well as
significantly pushing college operating costs), the
government would do well to make educational loans available
to all worthy applicants. The high rates of return to college
graduates would make this among the safer loans issued by our
financial institutions in recent years.
   Andrew Zimbalist
   Professor of Economics
   Smith College
   Northampton, Mass.
   ---
   I went to a state college (Frostburg), where I obtained a
good education. My professors were hard workers and their
classes were very interesting. Almost all of my professors
took an interest in my educational and professional future
after graduation. Now, I work as a librarian in a respectable
law firm.
   I cannot sympathize with parents who hold themselves
hostage to an expensive institution's tuition, because I know
that there is a bright alternative -- public higher
education.
   Harrison W. Burgess
   Hartford, Conn.
   ---
   Your complaint that "too often it looks as if the schools
exist mainly for the benefit of the faculty" is both naive
and misguided. Are not the tenured faculty members the de
facto proprietors of educational institutions? Are not
enterprises, in a free-enterprise economy, run for the
benefit of their proprietors? Do you take seriously the
rhetoric of college and university administrators who pretend
to be motivated by charitable rather than self-interested
objectives? Do you think that the not-for-profit tax loophole
really means not for profit?
   Most important, what is your problem with the profit
motive? You suggest that similar tuition at similar
institutions is evidence of collusion. But the market for
educational services, with thousands of suppliers and free
entry, actually is highly competitive. Students, who apply in
large numbers and cherish admission, clearly regard an
education at even the elite colleges and universities that
charge the highest tuition to be a bargain. In fact, the
interesting question is why demand has not driven tuition
substantially higher. (The answer presumably is that an
excess of applicants enables colleges and universities to
perform a useful screening function.)
   The bottom line is that Adam Smith's invisible hand works.
All studies show that a higher education is the best
investment a family can make. The self-interest of suppliers
constrained by competition has given us, as you grudgingly
admit, "the best university system in the world."
   Herschel I. Grossman
   Professor, Social Sciences, Economics
   Brown University
   Providence, R.I.
   ---
   You use the terms "average workload" and "teaching load"
interchangeably. In order to clarify your meaning for me and,
perhaps, for other readers as well, let me pose the following
question.
   Does an editorial writer for The Wall Street Journal have
an average workload calculated solely on the time his or her
fingers are actually inputting information via an electronic
keyboard, to the exclusion of time spent on research,
thinking, communicating, administering, meeting with
colleagues and perchance even drinking coffee?
   Willis F. Long
   Professor
   University of Wisconsin-Madison
   Madison, Wis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900419-0134
</DOCNO>
