<HL>
   Yields on Money Funds and Bank CDs
   Were Little Changed in the Latest Week
   ----
   By Georgette Jasen and Ellen E. Schultz
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C20
</SO>
<IN>
MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   Yields on both money-market mutual funds and bank
certificates of deposit were little changed in the latest
week.
   The average seven-day compound yield on taxable money
funds remained at 7.99%, according to IBC/Donoghue's Money
Fund Report, a Holliston, Mass.based newsletter. The average
yield on a small-denomination six-month CD stayed at 7.80%,
according to Banxquote Money Markets, a New York information
service. Compound yields assume reinvestment of dividends.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Yields on tax-free money funds rose, however.
   Assets of the 427 taxable money funds tracked by
Donoghue's fell by about $1.5 billion in the week ended
Tuesday, the third consecutive weekly decline. Brenda Malizia
Negus, editor of the newsletter, attributed the latest drop
in part to redemptions for tax purposes.
   Average maturity of the funds' investments shortened by a
day to 44 days, staying within the range of the past few
months. Maturities are thought to indicate which way
portfolio managers think interest rates are headed, with
shorter maturities signaling rising rates and longer
maturities indicating a decline. Average maturity has ranged
from 29 to 53 days in recent years.
   The average seven-day simple yield remained at 7.69%. The
average 30-day simple yield stayed at 7.68% and the average
30-day compound yield at 7.98%.
   The average seven-day compound yield on tax-free funds
rose to 5.63% from 5.57%, Donoghue's reported. That's equal
to 7.82% for an investor in the 28% tax bracket and 8.40% in
the 33% bracket.
   Assets of the 220 tax-free funds tracked by Donoghue's
fell by $1.3 billion, to $77.5 billion. Average maturity
shortened to 45 days from 46.
   The only measurable change in CD yields in the week ended
yesterday was in long-term "jumbo" CDs, which generally
require deposits of at least $90,000. The average yield on
five-year jumbos rose to 8.38% from 8.33%, according to
Banxquote. That increase was led by New York's Chase
Manhattan Bank, which boosted its five-year jumbo yield to
8.86% from 8.55% early last week.
   That sharp rise could portend other increases, said
Norberto Mehl, chairman of Banxquote. "When a major bank
suddenly pushes a rate up strongly, it points to a new
trend," he said.
   The average yield on popular one-year small-denomination
CDs, which generally require minimum deposits of $10,000 or
less, slipped to 7.95% from 7.96%. Fiveyear
small-denomination CD yields remained at an average 8.16%.
   ---
   Portfolio Changes
                                                                                                       

   Some money funds are moving to improve the credit quality
of their investments, after two instances when several funds'
investment advisers had to step in to avert possible
shareholder losses.
   T. Rowe Price Associates' $4.9 billion Prime Reserve money
fund, for instance, has reduced its commercial paper holdings
and increased its investments in government and agency
securities. The fund also has reduced its holdings of
commercial paper that doesn't carry the very highest credit
ratings, said Steven Norwitz, a T. Rowe Price vice president.
   Heritage Cash Trust has been upgrading its portfolio since
last year, said Stephen Hill, president of Heritage Asset
Management, the fund's investment adviser. Only 10% of the
fund's approximately $700 million in assets is currently in
paper that is below the highest grade, he said, and more than
10% is in Treasury bills.
   The two funds were among 10 moneymarket mutual funds
holding the commercial paper, or short-term corporate IOUs,
of Mortgage &amp; Realty Trust, an Elkins Park, Pa., real estate
investment trust that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy-law
protection last week, a month after its commercial paper was
downgraded by Standard &amp; Poor's Corp.
   All together, the investment advisers or parent companies
bought a total of about $75 million of the paper from the
funds to protect shareholders. Among others, Prime Reserve
held about $42 million of the paper, Heritage Cash Trust
about $12 million and Alliance Money Reserves $8.7 million.
"We consider it of paramount importance to retain investor
confidence," said Mr. Norwitz of T. Rowe Price. Any loss will
be absorbed by the parent company.
   There was similar fast action last spring, when the
parents of four money funds stepped in to absorb the loss
after Integrated Resources Inc. defaulted on commercial
paper. Integrated Resources also subsequently filed for
Chapter 11 protection.
   As previously reported, the Securities and Exchange
Commission is considering tighter restrictions on investments
by money-market mutual funds. The SEC's division of
investment management is planning to propose further limits
on the amount a fund can invest in a single issuer,
restrictions on its investments in less than the very highest
rated commercial paper and shortening the permissible average
maturity of a fund's investments.
   More than half the nearly $400 billion in money fund
assets currently is invested in commercial paper. That's up
from 44% at the start of 1989 and 29% at the start of 1984.
The SEC already limits money funds' investments to highly
rated securities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900419-0078
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900419-0078.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Brazil Planning
   New Discussions
   On Huge Debt
   ---
   Officials Also Set Timetable
   For Sale of Many Firms
   Owned by Government
   ----
   By Thomas Kamm
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM FORGN
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   BRASILIA, Brazil -- Confident that its bold anti-inflation
program is working, the Brazilian government plans to resume
negotiations on its $115 billion foreign debt and start its
drive to sell state companies in the coming weeks, senior
officials said.
   In separate interviews here, Economics Minister Zelia
Cardoso de Mello and Central Bank President Ibrahim Eris said
the government, after winning the endorsement of Brazil's
Congress last week for its stabilization program, will begin
a "new phase" of the program, which will include:
</LP>
<TEXT>
   -- Resumption of negotiations with Brazil's foreign
creditors, beginning with the International Monetary Fund, as
early as next month. But officials say Brazil will adopt a
"tough stance."
   -- The start next month of the government's ambitious plan
to sell most of Brazil's 188 state-controlled companies,
which have a combined deficit of $62 billion. Ms. Cardoso
said the program would start with Usiminas, a profitable
steelmaker.
   -- Efforts to start lowering the non-tariff barriers that
have effectively shielded the Brazilian economy from
competition.
   -- The dismantling in the weeks ahead of most of the price
controls the government imposed last month as part of its
anti-inflation program. Mr. Eris says the controls contradict
the government's freemarket aims and are "redundant" because
of the anti-inflation plan's initial success.
   Indeed, the unveiling of the new phase of the plan
coincides with indications that Brazil's chronic inflation,
which reached 4,854% in the past 12 months, could be on the
way out. Because of the huge liquidity squeeze that forms the
centerpiece of the plan -- the government took about $80
billion out of circulation by freezing a large part of
savings and money market accounts for 18 months -- Brazil
expects to post negative inflation of between 0.5% and 1% for
the 30-day period since the the program was unveiled March
16.
   Ms. Cardoso said the figure shows the plan is "working
well" and added that she saw "no reason why inflation should
return" even though the government is prepared to reinject
money in the economy to help the beleaguered automobile,
construction and capital-goods industries.
   But Mr. Eris, striking a more cautionary note echoed by
many economists, says Brazil runs the risk of falling into
recession or returning to high inflation unless the economy
is properly tuned.
   Walter Barelli, an economist affiliated with a Brazilian
union research organization, disputed the government's
estimate of zero inflation and predicted steep price
increases.
   On Brazil's foreign debt of $115 billion, the developing
world's largest, Ms. Cardoso said she would resume contacts
with creditors by attending the IMF's interim committee
meeting in Washington in early May. Brazil hasn't paid
interest on its $65 billion of medium-term and long-term bank
debt since September. That failure in the past several days
helped to depress the first-quarter earnings of big U.S.
banks.
   But Mr. Eris warned creditors against expecting much from
Brazil. "Brazil's stance will be tough," he said.
"Arrangements can be flexible as long as they're compatible
with our payments capacity. Brazil needs to grow without
inflation," he added, "and for that we need savings and
investment rates comparable to those of other countries."
   Ms. Cardoso said reports that Brazil would limit its
payments to about $5 billion a year were reasonable. However,
it isn't clear how the payments would be distributed among
Brazil's multilateral, government and bank creditors.
   By unveiling plans to sell off Usiminas next month, Ms.
Cardoso indicated the government intends to move fast to kick
off its privatization campaign and address charges that the
private sector bears the burden of the adjustment plan. Mr.
Eris said many other sales are planned.
   "Everything is on sale except a few companies," such as
oil giant Petrobras and the Banco do Brasil commercial bank,
which have to remain in the public sector under the
privatization bill, Mr. Eris said. "And I don't only mean the
companies," he added. "I mean houses, buildings and cars
owned by the state too."
   On foreign trade, Mr. Eris said the government hopes to
eliminate all controls on imports by the end of the year,
maintaining tariffs only as a policy instrument.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
