   New Securities Issues
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP FRE SLM CHL FORGN F.RNA
</CO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
BANKS (BNK)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                       CORPORATES
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Ontario Hydro -- $600 million of notes, due May 1, 1995,
was priced at par to yield 9.25%. The non-callable notes were
priced at a spread of 0.50 percentage point above the
Treasury's five-year note. The size of the issue was
increased from $500 million. Rated triple-A by Moody's
Investors Service Inc. and Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., the issue
will be sold through underwriters led by Salomon Brothers
Inc. Ontario Hydro is the largest Canadian utility.
                                                                                                       

                        MUNICIPALS
                                                                                                       

   Puerto Rico Housing Finance Authority -- $173 million of
multi-family mortgage revenue bonds, Portfolio A, Series I,
due Oct. 1 and April 1, 1990-2007, 2011, 2015 and 2022, were
tentatively priced by a Citicorp Securities Markets Inc.
group to yield from 5.90% in 1990 to 7.60% in 2022. Current
interest serial bonds are priced to yield from 5.90% in 1990
to 7.40% in 2007. The $28.7 million of term bonds due in 2011
aren't being formally reoffered. There are $29.2 million of 7
1/2% term bonds priced at 99 1/4 to yield 7.57% in 2015 and
$64.8 million of 7 1/2% term bonds priced at 98 3/4 to yield
7.60% in 2022. The bonds are rated double-A by S&amp;P and are
secured by a letter of credit from Government Development
Bank for Puerto Rico.
   Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority -- $85
million of sales tax revenue bonds, Series L, due July 1,
1991-2007, 2010 and 2020 are seen won by a First Boston Corp.
group with a bid setting the true interest cost at 7.3237%.
Earlier, the deal, which was priced via competitive bidding
was seen won by a Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. group, but it was
later awarded to the First Boston group. As priced by First
Boston, the bonds, rated single-A by Moody's and
single-A-plus by S&amp;P, were priced for reoffering to yield
from 6.00% in 1991 to 7.27% in 2010. Current interest serial
bonds are priced to yield from 6.00% in 1991 to 7.20% in 2006
and 2007. There are $9.2 million of 7.20% term bonds priced
at 99 1/4 to yield 7.27% in 2010 and $49.1 million of 7.20%
term bonds priced at 99 3/8 to yield 7.25% in 2020. Bonds
maturing in 2020 are insured and rated triple-A by Moody's
and S&amp;P.
   Wisconsin -- $65.9 million of general obligation bonds,
Higher Education Series, 1990 Series D, capital appreciation
bonds, due May 1, 1996-2010, were tentatively priced by a
Merrill Lynch Capital Markets group to yield to maturity from
6.50% in 1996 to 7.00% in 2007-2010. The bonds are rated
double-A by Moody's and S&amp;P. The bonds will be targeted
toward retail investors.
                                                                                                       

                         MORTGAGES
                                                                                                       

   Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. -- $500 million of real
estate mortgage investment conduit securities is being
offered in 19 classes by Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. The offering,
Series 165, is backed by Freddie Mac 9 1/2% securities, with
an underlying weighted average coupon rate of 10.125% and
weighted average remaining term to maturity of 29.4 years.
Full details on yields weren't immediately available. Also a
$300 million issue of Remic securities is being offered by
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. The issue, Freddie Mac's
Series 166, is backed by Freddie Mac 9 1/2% securities.
Details weren't immediately available.
                                                                                                       

                       ASSET-BACKED
                                                                                                       

   Chemical Financial Acceptance Corp. -- $119.7 million of
securities backed by loans on recreational vehicles with a
coupon rate of 9 1/2% at 99.328 to yield 9.81% through
Chemical Securities Inc. and Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. The
issue is being made through CFAC Grantor Trust 1990-B, which
is holding loans sold by Chemical Financial Acceptance, a
unit of Chemical Banking Corp. The securities were priced at
a yield spread of 1.05 percentage points above the Treasury
three-year note. The issue has an estimated average life of
3.2 years assuming monthly prepayments at 1% of the original
loan balance. The final maturity date is in April 1997. The
securities are expected to carry triple-A ratings from S&amp;P
and Duff &amp; Phelps, based on the quality of the underlying
loans and a surety bond, or guarantee, covering 10% of the
deal from Capital Markets Assurance Corp., an insurance
company owned by Citicorp. The underlying loans have a
weighted average remaining term to maturity of 12.25 years.
                                                                                                       

                           OTHER
                                                                                                       

   Student Loan Marketing Association -- $150 million of
notes, due May 8, 1995, was priced at par for an initial
yield of 9.12%. The notes, which are non-callable for three
years, will be reoffered at various prices through
underwriters led by Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. They were priced at
a spread of 0.41 percentage point above the Treasury's
five-year note.
                                                                                                       

                      EUROBONDS
                                                                                                       

   Restructured Obligations backed by Senior Assets, Rosa BV
(special-purpose vehicle) -- $1 billion three-tranche
leveraged buy-out loan-backed bonds via Nomura International
Ltd. First tranche consists of $300 million of senior secured
securities priced at par and set to float at 0.30 percentage
point above the three-month London interbank offered rate.
Second tranche consists of secured senior subordinated
securities priced at par and set to float at 0.75 percentage
point above the three-month Libor. Final $200 million tranche
is a private placement. Maturity date for two public
offerings is March 10, 1998.
   World Bank (agency) -- 400 billion lire ($325.6 million)
of 12 1/8% bonds due May 17, 1995, priced at 101.30 to yield
12.25% via lead manager Banca Nazionale del Lavoro.
   CSFB Effectenbank AG (West Germany) -- 350 million marks
($209.3 million) of fiduciary floating-rate notes at the
six-month Libor, with an issue price of 100.20 and due May
1994, via CSFB Effectenbank AG. Bond is to fund a loan to the
Italian-based Crediop. Payment of interest and principal will
be made only with funds paid to CSFB by Crediop. Callable
from May 1992 at par.
   Britannia Building Society (United Kingdom) -- #100
million ($163.9 million) of floating-rate notes due May 1994,
paying 1/10 point above the Libor, priced at par, via Hambros
Bank. Put option at par after two years.
   LTCB Finance NV (Japanese parent ) -- $125 million of
bonds due May 18, 2000, priced at 102 via LTCB International
Ltd. Coupon of 10 1/8% for the first two years, then 10%.
Once-only call at par on May 18, 1992. Guaranteed by Long
Term Credit Bank Ltd.
   Caisse Autonome de Refinancement (France) -- $100 million
of floating-rate notes due May 1995, priced at par and paying
interest at six-month Libor less 0.145 percentage point, via
Credit Lyonnais.
   Renault Acceptance BV (French parent) -- 75 million Swiss
francs ($50.7 million) of 7 3/4% privately placed notes due
May 17, 1995, priced at 101 1/4 via Union Bank of
Switzerland. Guarantee by Renault Credit International of
Paris.
