</DOCID>
<HL>
   Democrats on House Budget Panel Split
   Over Proposed Cuts in Military Spending
   ----
   By Jeffrey H. Birnbaum
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES (HHS)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Military-spending provisions of the House
Budget Committee chairman's deficit-reduction blueprint ran
into dissension among members of his own Democratic Party.
   Only a few hours after House Speaker Thomas Foley
predicted that the fiscal 1991 budget resolution would pass
the House, committee Democrats huddled in private to discuss
vigorous demands by angry liberals that part of the military
spending budget be reduced even further than Chairman Leon
Panetta (D., Calif.) had recommended. Committee members gave
strong indications last evening that the spending-authority
portion of the military budget would be reduced.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But that change, if made, could alienate conservative
members of the Democratic Party and create additional
problems for the budget blueprint. The committee has
scheduled a drafting session for today to discuss the
document. The Republican minority on the committee is
expected to oppose the Panetta plan entirely, leaving its
fate fully in the hands of the Democrats. Whatever the
committee decides, amendments could also be made on the House
floor.
   As expected, the Panetta proposal calls for a cut in
military outlays of $11.5 billion and a tax increase of $13.9
billion.
   The contentious element in the military-spending debate is
a category separate from outlays, called spending authority.
The Panetta plan would set spending authority at $286
billion; the liberals are aiming to trim that number to $283
billion, which would have the effect of reducing outlays, or
actual expenditures, in future years. Actual military
spending under the Panetta plan would total $295 billion in
fiscal 1991, which starts Oct. 1.
   The military-spending level is only one hurdle faced by
Rep. Panetta. The other is that it remains unclear at best
how much of the blueprint will ultimately be translated into
law. More than half the $36.2 billion in the deficit
reduction proposed in the document, including all of the tax
increase, is contingent on negotiations with President Bush,
and, so far at least, neither the president nor the
Democratic leaders in Congress have shown much more than
rhetorical interest in compromise.
   The goal of the budget resolution is to lay out a
blueprint for spending and tax legislation by other
committees. It is designed to reduce the deficit in fiscal
1991 to $64 billion from the projected deficit of $100.5
billion that would occur without new legislation.
   The resolution doesn't require the president's signature,
but Democrats made clear it will require his acquiescence if
it is to be put into effect. Speaking of talks with the
president, Speaker Foley, a Washington Democrat, said, "There
is a sense that we may become more engaged later on."
   In the meantime, Rep. Panetta, backed by the House
Democratic leadership, offered a plan yesterday that gets the
bulk of its savings from a combination of militaryspending
reductions that are deeper than the White House wants, and
tax increases that haven't yet been negotiated with a
president who is reluctant at best to accept any.
   In addition, the plan claims $9.1 billion in savings from
an amorphous cluster of proposals that are almost solely
reliant on actions by the executive branch and that
congressional Democrats had previously derided as illusory.
They include, for example, a $3 billion savings from a
reorganization of the Internal Revenue Service.
   The Panetta plan covers fiscal year 1991, but it also
purports to make recommendations for budget savings over five
years. It also urges removal of the Social Security trust
fund from the regular budget-deficit calculation under the
Gramm-Rudman law. Legislation to authorize that change is
likely to come later this year, Mr. Panetta said.
   The Panetta plan is the Democrats' first detailed response
to President Bush's own budget plan. Compared with the
president's plan, the Panetta plan seeks almost $8 billion
less in military outlays, far fewer cuts in nonmilitary
spending, especially in Medicare and farm subsidies, and also
recommends $6 billion in new spending on programs ranging
from child care to space exploration. Rep. Panetta said it
represents a transition from "a Cold War economy to a
peacetime economy."
   The Senate Budget Committee, its work delayed by the
funeral in Hawaii of Sen. Spark Matsunaga, is planning to
begin work on its budget resolution next week.
   ---
   David Rogers contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900419-0055
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900419-0055.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   General Dynamics
   And Northrop Post
   Increases in Net
   ----
   By Rick Wartzman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9
</SO>
<CO>
   GD NOC
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<LP>
   ST. LOUIS -- General Dynamics Corp., buffeted by lower
earnings in nearly all of its businesses, said operating
results for the first quarter fell 17.5%, but a $61.5 million
windfall boosted net income by 64%.
   The gain, which came from the settlement of an antitrust
lawsuit with American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., lifted net
income to $123.7 million, or $2.97 a share. A year earlier,
the company earned $75.4 million, or $1.81 a share. Revenue
rose 5% to $2.49 billion from $2.36 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Meanwhile, Los Angeles-based Northrop Corp.'s first
quarter net income soared to $96 million, or $2.04 a share,
from $9.7 million, or 21 cents a share. Earnings for the
latest period included $67.1 million from the sale of
Northrop's corporate headquarters complex.
   Northrop's operating earnings also increased sharply,
rising threefold as the company recovered from a year-ago
writedown in its electronics segment. Sales were flat at
$1.28 billion.
   In some ways, though, the tales of these two arms makers
showed how misleading quarterly figures can be in trying to
predict the future. Northrop, for example, turned in a
relatively impressive operating performance in part because
of stepped up production on the B-2 Stealth bomber. But that
programs seems, over the long term, to be in a particularly
precarious position with Washington budget-cutters.
   By contrast, General Dynamics is incurring squeezed profit
margins at its F-16 fighter factory because it is "staggering
under the work load" of trying to churn out several versions
of the plane simultaneously, James Cunnane, chief financial
officer, said in an interview here. He added that "there is
constant pressure" also being applied to meet schedules on
two other aircraft programs, the A-12 for the Navy and the
Advanced Tactical Fighter for the Air Force.
   At the same time, Mr. Cunnane pointed out, General
Dynamics is spending development dollars on the Atlas rocket,
but it won't begin to record income on the program until the
first launch, which is set for the third quarter.
   "We're suffering from the inefficiencies of expansion," he
said. "I expect that we're going to be in this mode for a
while."
   Northrop's real estate sale also helped it reduce debt to
$881 million from $1.12 billion at the end of 1989. The
balance of its after-tax gain, $22.8 million, will be
deferred and amortized into income over the 10-year lease of
the space in the building Northrop now occupies.
   Operating margins in this year's first quarter included
the recognition of $10.7 million in pension income, as
compared with $3.2 million in pension costs a year before.
   Profits in the aircraft group at Northrop slumped to $56.8
million from $79.3 million, which was in step with a decline
in F/A-18 fighter sales to prime contractor McDonnell Douglas
Corp. and 747 component sales to Boeing Co. Earnings on the
electronics side improved, however, to $8.4 million from a
$13.7 million loss last year when the company made a $26
million provision in connection with research expenses on a
system for the F-15 fighter.
   The biggest winner at General Dynamics was its Cessna
unit, which manufactures small planes. Earnings there leaped
to $16.5 million from $4.3 million.
   But, in the current environment, it would be incorrect to
describe any defense contractor as being in enviable shape.
"General Dynamics is just a microcosm of the defense budget,"
said George Shapiro, aerospace analyst at Salomon Brothers
Inc. "They're going to feel a steady deterioration in their
profit margins."
   He noted that in the first quarter, the company
experienced such problems on the Trident submarine. On top of
that, margins were tighter on the Standard, Phalanx and
Tomahawk missiles, where General Dynamics's role slipped to
that of a second-source supplier. The company once enjoyed
the lead on all of those projects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900419-0054
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900419-0054.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Bank of New England Corp.:
   Connecticut Bank &amp; Trust
   Is Told to Tighten Policies
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   NEB
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   The Comptroller of the Currency directed Bank of New
England Corp.'s Connecticut Bank &amp; Trust Co. subsidiary to
tighten its lending policies and management oversight in a
consent cease-and-desist order.
   The Comptroller also cited a violation of law applicable
to the bank, but the Treasury Department office declined to
give further details.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Bank of New England is already operating under a similar
order, and the Connecticut order was expected. Its provisions
include a requirement that the bank maintain an equity
capital-to-total assets ratio of at least 3% and develop a
timetable through 1991 to achieve and maintain a ratio of at
least 5%.
   In a statement, Connecticut Bank &amp; Trust called the plans
and procedures outlined in the order "sound measures that any
bank should follow" and said that "many of the changes called
for are already under way."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900419-0053
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900419-0053.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   LITHUANIA SAID the Soviet Union severed oil supplies to
the Baltic republic.
   Despite an offer by lawmakers in Vilnius to cease
secession-related legislative action if the Kremlin opens
immediate talks, a spokesman for Lithuania's legislature said
Moscow cut off the supply of oil to the republic's only
refinery. It wasn't known whether natural-gas deliveries also
had been disrupted as part of Gorbachev's threatened economic
embargo. Lithuania, which proclaimed its independence March
11, is entirely dependent on the Soviet Union for energy
supplies.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State Baker renewed a warning to Moscow,
saying action against Lithuania could doom U.S. and Soviet
commercial relations.
   ---
   THE JUSTICES BACKED a judge's power to order school
desegregation funds.
   Defying expectations, a divided Supreme Court reaffirmed
the authority of courts to correct constitutional violations,
ruling that a federal judge may require a Kansas City, Mo.,
school district to raise taxes to pay for desegregation. The
court also said a judge may block enforcement of state laws
that interfere with funding the plan. At the same time,
however, the justices said there must be limits on the
enforcement power of federal judges.
   The court, voting 6-3 in an Ohio case, ruled that a state
may make it illegal to possess or view child pornography,
even in the privacy of one's home.
   ---
   Pro-Iranian kidnappers in Lebanon said they would release
by tomorrow one of three American educators as a humanitarian
gesture. The announcement by the group Islamic Jihad for the
Liberation of Palestine, which was accompanied by a
photograph of hostage Jesse Turner, said the captive would
carry a message for Bush.
   ---
   Bush closed an international conference on global warming
by ignoring the differences among the delegates. Speaking at
the end of the two-day parley in Washington aimed at forging
a policy on the greenhouse effect, the president said the
U.S. had "never considered research a substitute for action"
on the issue.
   ---
   A new cancer drug proved successful with very few side
effects in treating a relatively rare form of leukemia,
researchers said. The drug, 2-CdA, produced nearly complete
remissions in 12 patients with hairy-cell leukemia who
underwent one seven-day treatment.
   ---
   Britain's government confirmed that steel tubes seized
last week by officials in England are parts for a huge gun
bound for Iraq. It was the first high-level acknowledgment of
the pipes' military potential. But experts remain puzzled by
the workings of such a weapon.
   ---
   East and West Germany opened negotiations on
reunification, and Bonn said talks on a monetary union could
start tomorrow. West Germany's ZDF television network,
meanwhile, reported that the Kremlin has told East German
Prime Minister de Maiziere that it opposes quick unification.
   ---
   Major universities are warning the Pentagon that a
military policy barring homosexuals from service is
generating pressure to oust ROTC from campuses. Groups from
MIT, the University of Wisconsin, Northwestern and elsewhere
have protested the officer-training corps policy. The
Pentagon has declined to comment on the issue.
   ---
   NASA advanced the date for the second launch attempt of
the space shuttle Discovery, saying the spacecraft and the
Hubble Space Telescope are ready for a Tuesday liftoff. The
launch had been set for Wednesday, 15 days after the first
attempt was scrubbed because of a faulty power unit.
   ---
   A rifle-fired grenade slammed into a school bus during
Christian factional fighting in Lebanon, killing at least 11
children and four other people. Police said the vehicle was
hit while crossing into mainly Christian eastern Beirut as it
was returning from the southern part of the capital.
   ---
   A series of earthquakes rattled Northern California, but
didn't cause major damage or injuries. The temblors, the
hardest registering 5.4 on the Richter scale, shook a 100mile
area from San Francisco to Salinas on the anniversary of the
1906 quake.
   ---
   Mexico demanded that Washington explain the seizure of a
Mexican doctor charged in the 1985 murder of U.S. drug agent
Enrique Camarena. The physician reportedly was kidnapped by
bounty hunters and brought to Los Angeles this month.
   ---
   Nepal's prime minister-designate named eight cabinet
ministers to form the Himalayan kingdom's first
opposition-led government in almost 30 years. The official,
dissident K.P. Bhattarai, said he would retain the defense
and foreign portfolios. The list was sent to King Birendra
for approval.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900419-0052
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900419-0052.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Abreast of the Market:
   Stocks Fall as Interest Rates Surge;
   Retail, Technology Lead Decline
   ----
   By David Wilson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The stock market suffered its worst setback in
nearly two months as a surge in interest rates sent prices
tumbling.
   Retailing and technology issues were among the major
casualties of the sell-off, which was fueled by
futures-related program selling that gained momentum as the
session progressed.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Blue-chip stocks, which have generally been performing
better than the broad market lately, weren't able to maintain
their dominance. The Dow Jones Industrial Average skidded
32.89 to 2732.88, and other market measures recorded
comparable losses.
   Standard &amp; Poor's 500-Stock Index fell 3.96 to 340.72, the
New York Stock Exchange Composite Index went down 1.98 to
186.93 and the Dow Jones Equity Market Index fell 3.61 to
317.47. Decliners led by 1,056 issues on the Big Board, over
477 advancers.
   Prices briefly moved higher in opening trading in response
to February trade figures, which was better than expected.
The data showed that the nation's trade deficit narrowed
sharply, to $6.49 billion from $9.32 billion in February.
   But as bond prices plunged for a second straight day amid
widespread speculation that Japanese investors were heavy
sellers of U.S. Treasury issues, stocks proved unable to hold
those gains.
   Sell programs resulting from stock-index arbitrage first
surfaced in the market at late morning, traders said. The
programs, involving the purchase of index-futures contracts
and the sale of baskets of stocks to profit from price
differences between them, struck again several times during
the afternoon.
   As the Dow industrial average posted its sharpest loss
since Feb. 20, when the 30-stock average declined 38.74,
trading activity on the Big Board swelled to its highest
level since April 4. Volume totaled 147,130,000 shares on the
Big Board, up from 127,990,000 Tuesday.
   Even so, traders said selling pressure didn't appear to be
especially heavy, as many investors remained out of the
market. "They don't want to get involved because they don't
know what's going to happen," said Kenneth P. Ducey, senior
vice president of institutional trading at S.G. Warburg.
   Prices on long-term Treasury issues fell 1 1/8 points, or
$11.25 per $1,000 face amount. The benchmark 30-year issue
had a yield of 8.83%, the highest since May of last year, and
up from 8.72% Tuesday.
   "The weakness in bonds over the last few days is taking
its toll on the equity market," said Peter VandenBerg, a vice
president of equity trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton.
   Traders said the arbitrage-related selling in the
afternoon was concentrated in futures contracts on the Major
Market Index, a 20-stock average designed to mirror the Dow
industrials. The index includes 17 issues that are also in
the 30-stock average.
   Higher rates also encouraged market participants to take
profits stemming from the market's recent move toward the
upper end of the trading range that has prevailed since
January, traders said. The Dow industrials, at Tuesday's
close, stood just 1.6% below the record high of 2810.15, set
Jan. 2.
   Technology stocks, which had benefited recently from the
strong first-quarter results reported by International
Business Machines and Motorola, were among the most prominent
targets of profit-taking.
   IBM dropped 1 1/4 to 109 7/8 and Motorola fell 3/4 to 67
7/8. Among other issues, Digital Equipment retreated 1 7/8 to
80, Hewlett Packard slipped 1 1/8 to 43 1/2, Compaq Computer
eased 1 1/8 to 99 1/2, Cray Research skidded 1 3/8 to 45 1/2
and Texas Instruments fell 1 1/4 to 36 3/8.
   However, Tandem Computers rose 1 1/8 to 24 1/8 in Big
Board composite trading of two million shares as its earnings
report for the fiscal second quarter, ended in March, was
well-received. The company reported that net income rose more
than 59% from the year-ago period, and its earnings per share
of 25 cents was in line with analysts' recent forecasts.
   Among retailing stocks, another strong group recently,
shares of specialty retailers were hit the hardest. Tandy
declined 1 3/4 to 32 1/2, Limited Inc. dropped 7/8 to 41 3/4,
Gap Inc. fell 1 1/2 to 64 1/2, Circuit City Stores dropped
3/4 to 25 3/4 and Toys "R" Us slid 7/8 to 42 1/8.
   Woolworth, which owns several specialty chains, dropped
7/8 to 61 3/4. As for other major retailers, Dayton Hudson
fell 1 to 70 3/4, J.C. Penney fell 1 to 68 3/4, Wal- Mart
Stores declined 1 1/8 to 49 3/8 and Dillard Department Stores
dropped 2 3/8 to 72 7/8.
   McKesson, which said it is boosting reserves for accounts
receivable because of concern about the financial health of
some of its retail customers, tumbled 2 1/4 to 34 3/8. The
company didn't specify the amount of the increase, but said
its earnings for the fiscal fourth quarter and year ended in
March will be below year-earlier levels.
   Merck, the best performer among the 30 stocks in the Dow
industrials, gained 5/8 to 74 3/8 after reporting
first-quarter earnings that exceeded the expectations of most
analysts. The company's net income rose about 19% from the
year-earlier level.
   Philip Morris, whose net for the quarter was also better
than expected, dropped 3/8 to 42 5/8 on 2.4 million shares
after trading at higher levels for most of the session. The
company's earnings rose 31%.
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph dropped 1 to 41 despite
reporting that first-quarter net was 11% higher than a year
ago. Analysts had expected a better performance. Among other
blue-chip companies issuing quarterly reports, United
Technologies dipped 3/8 to 57 and Coca-Cola fell 1 to 79 1/4.
   Stocks to benefit from positive earnings surprises
included First Interstate Bancorp, which rose 7/8 to 36, and
Phelps Dodge, which gained 1/2 to 61 7/8. Although
first-quarter net at both companies fell short of year-ago
levels, the declines weren't as sharp as had been expected.
   Conversely, Polaroid fell 1 3/4 to 43 3/4 after posting a
disappointing 23% rise in its first-quarter earnings. The
company also scaled back its projected earnings growth for
this year to "moderate" from "substantially higher"; it
didn't provide a specific forecast.
   Nervousness about the rate outlook proved favorable for
precious-metals issues, generally viewed as a safe haven for
investors. Homestake Mining rose 1 to 17 3/4, Placer Dome
added 3/4 to 17, Battle Mountain Gold advanced 1/2 to 14 3/8
and ASA Ltd. rose 2 1/8 to 51 7/8.
   Auto issues also escaped the worst of the downturn.
General Motors added 1/8 to close at 46 on 1.6 million
shares. Trading also was heavy in Ford Motor, which rose 7/8
to 48, and Chrysler, which slid 1/8 to 16 3/4.
   Mattel rose 3/8 to 22 3/8 after Merrill Lynch raised its
long-term investment rating on the stock to the firm's
highest level. Merrill Lynch also reiterated its buy
recommendation on Blockbuster Entertainment, which gained 1/8
to 18 3/8.
   Thomson McKinnon Asset Management jumped 1 7/8 to 8.
Thomson McKinnon Inc., which holds a 63% interest in the
partnership, agreed in principle to sell its stake to three
of the unit's managers.
   CML Group fell 1 1/8 to 21 1/8. Investor Irwin Jacobs
dropped plans for a proxy fight to replace its board with a
slate committed to its sale. Separately, CML estimated that
it would report a loss of $1.90 to $2 a share for the fiscal
year ending in July.
   The American Stock Exchange Market Value Index fell 1.50
to 353.22. Volume totaled 13,370,000 shares compared with
13,510,000 Tuesday. There were 202 issues advancing and 352
declining.
   American Fructose class A skidded 2 3/8 to 21 1/8. The
company reported that first-quarter earnings fell about 10%
from a year ago, while sales dropped 6%.
</TEXT>
