<HL>
   McKesson to Take
   4th-Period Charge;
   Stock Falls Sharply
   ----
   By Ken Wells
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   MCK
</CO>
<IN>
DRUG-BASED RETAILERS AND WHOLESALERS, PHARMACIES (RTD)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<LP>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- Debt burdened retailers are giving
McKesson Corp. a big headache.
   Stock of the drug distribution giant plunged $2.25 to
$34.375 yesterday following an announcement that it was
taking a sizable charge against fiscal fourth-quarter
earnings because some of its highly leveraged retail
customers had fallen behind on their bills.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   McKesson declined to give a dollar figure for the
reserves. But the company said the charge would depress
earnings for the quarter ended March 31 "significantly" below
the $25.4 million, or 59 cents a share, it earned in the
year-earlier period. McKesson also said full fiscal-year
profit would be down "modestly" from year-earlier levels,
when it posted a profit of $100.6 million, or $2.28 a share.
   One analyst estimated the charge at between $10 million
and $15 million and said that while McKesson had forecast
problems with its accounts receivables, the size of the
reserves came as something of a surprise.
   "We expected McKesson to take a charge but weren't
thinking of anything this large," said David Keuler of Blunt,
Ellis &amp; Loew, a Milwaukee research concern. On the "positive
side, we think McKesson has pretty much taken all of the
reserves it's going to need" to cover the problem bills, Mr.
Keuler added.
   McKesson said it decided to take the charge against
earnings after a two-month credit review showed that some of
its retail customers had "employed excessive leverage in
recent years and are using their suppliers to supplement
their bank credit lines." McKesson declined to name the
retailers but analysts said they likely include a big East
Coast department store chain as well as a nationwide chain of
convenience stores that carry McKesson products.
   "Given the narrow margins inherent in the distribution
business, the risk-reward ratio for McKesson to act as an
unsecured creditor in those situations is not consistent with
prudent business practices," the company said.
   The negative stock market reaction to McKesson wasn't
helped any by a separate announcement that fiscal
fourth-quarter earnings for its 83%-owned Armor All Products
unit would be "disappointing." McKesson declined to elaborate
but analysts said results of the car-care products subsidiary
would likely be negatively affected by a recent change in
accounting for marketing costs, a change in buying habits of
automobile-care retailers and by a general slowdown in sales
of Armor All products.
   "Growth in Armor All is kind of slow," said Mr. Kueler of
Blunt, Ellis. "Cars these days are being built with better
finishes, which means people don't need as many products as
they used to."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900419-0047
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900419-0047.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   House Passes Bill
   Aimed at Fighting
   Price Conspiracies
   ----
   By Paul M. Barrett
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<IN>
BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)
SPECIALTY APPAREL RETAILERS (SAP)
DRUG-BASED RETAILERS AND WHOLESALERS, PHARMACIES (RTD)
SPECIALTY RETAILERS (OTS)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The House approved a bill designed to make
it easier for discount retailers to sue competing retailers
and manufacturers that conspire to fix prices.
   The legislation, passed 235-157, has prompted threats of a
presidential veto from senior Bush administration officials.
The Senate Judiciary Committee has passed a similar bill,
which is expected to face stiff Republican opposition when it
goes before the full Senate later this year.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Proponents of the House legislation, led by Rep. Jack
Brooks (D., Texas), said it will facilitate lawsuits against
manufacturers and retailers that conspire to lock out
low-price retailers or to pressure discounters into raising
their prices. This illegal practice, known as resale price
maintenance, has become more prevalent because of lax federal
antitrust enforcement over the past nine years, according to
Mr. Brooks and his allies.
   The Justice Department hasn't brought a resale price
maintenance case since the beginning of the Reagan
administration. The department's inaction has inhibited
private lawsuits, according to proponents of the bill.
   The Supreme Court, in two decisions since 1984, has
increased the evidentiary burden on plaintiffs that claim to
be victims of manufacturer-retailer collusion. These
decisions, while not legalizing the practice, provided
considerable legal protection to defendants that conspire in
ways other than setting minimum prices, according to many
lawyers.
   The House bill and its Senate counterpart would clarify
that resale price maintenance is always illegal. In addition,
the bills would overturn Supreme Court precedent by
establishing that even without collusion on a specific price,
a manufacturer can't agree with one retailer to terminate a
competing retailer's supply contract.
   Consumer advocacy groups hailed House passage of the
legislation as a major victory. But the Justice Department
reiterated that it will urge President Bush to veto any such
bill that is sent to the White House. Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh has warned that the Brooks bill would interfere
with "the freedom of a manufacturer unilaterally to decide
whether or not to deal with a distributor, {which} is an
essential part of our free enterprise system."
   The House approved an amendment to the Brooks bill that
would exclude retroactive application of certain aspects of
the legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
