<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<LP>
   MUTUAL FUNDS with sales-related charges called 12b-1 fees
generally couldn't charge investors more than 7.25% of sales,
under a proposal by the National Association of Securities
Dealers. However, investors who hold their shares for a long
time may be forced to pay more than the 7.25% level.
Yesterday's edition misstated the proposed fee structure.
   (See: "NASD Proposes Limit on Fees Set by Funds" -- WSJ
April 18, 1990)
</LP>
<TEXT>
   ---
   VIACOM Inc. is approximately 84% owned by National
Amusements Inc. Yesterday's advertising column misstated the
relationship between the two companies.
   (See: "Marketing &amp; Media -- Advertising: Warner Bros.
Plans an Offensive Against Ads in Movie Theaters" -- WSJ
April 18, 1990)
   ---
   BALDWIN TECHNOLOGY Co. produces accessories and controls
for printing equipment. In Tuesday's edition it was
incorrectly indicated that the company was considering
expanding into manufacturing printing presses.
   (See: "Baldwin Technology Is Planning to Acquire
Dyson-Kissner Units" -- WSJ April 17, 1990)
   ---
   EECO Inc. expects to report a $10.3 million 1989 net loss.
The loss was misstated in Tuesday's edition.
   (See: "Business Brief -- Eeco Inc.: Net Loss of $1.4
Million Estimated for Jan. 1 Year" -- WSJ April 17, 1990)
