<HL>
   Business Brief -- Tandem Computers Inc.:
   Fiscal 2nd-Quarter Profit
   Climbed 59%, Revenue 24%
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   TDM
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Tandem Computers Inc. said fiscal second-quarter net
income surged 59% on the strength of new product sales and a
tight rein on expenses. Revenue rose 24%.
   The Cupertino, Calif., computer concern posted a profit of
$26.8 million, or 25 cents a share, on revenue of $451.3
million for the quarter ended March 31. It earned $16.9
million, or 17 cents a share, on revenue of $363.4 million,
in the year-earlier period.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   For the six-month period, Tandem said profit grew 20% to
$57.6 million, or 53 cents a share, from $48.2 million, or 48
cents a share. Revenue was up 17% to $887.8 million from
$755.7 million a year earlier.
   Tandem makes computers with automatic backup systems that
are used by stock exchanges and banks, among others, to run
sophisticated financial systems.
   Tandem stock rose $1.125 a share yesterday to close at
$24.125 in New York Stock Exchange composite trading.
</TEXT>
