<HL>
   Apple's Profit
   Spurted by 134%
   In 2nd Quarter
   ---
   Revenue Advanced by 8%;
   Computer Concern Cites
   Improved Margins, Sales
   ----
   By Ken Wells
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   AAPL
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   CUPERTINO, Calif. -- Apple Computer Inc. said fiscal
second-quarter profit surged 134% as a result of improved
gross margins, brisk sales of new products and robust foreign
sales.
   The company posted net income of $131.8 million, or $1.04
a share, for the quarter ended March 31, up from $56.4
million, or 44 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue climbed
8% to $1.35 billion from $1.25 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   For the six months, Apple said net spurted 30% to $256.7
million, or $2 a share, from $196.8 million, or $1.54 a
share, the year earlier. Revenue rose 7% to $2.84 billion
from $2.65 billion.
   Analysts said they were expecting a strong quarter from
Apple but that the results exceeded even those expectations.
The key appears to have been Apple's ability to wrench its
profit margins up to a "spectacular 55%, which has to be a
record or a near record," said Steven Ossad , a computer
analyst with Montgomery Securities in San Francisco.
   The good news, however, was tempered by Apple's forecast,
delivered to analysts during a conference call on Wednesday,
that its profit margins would fall from those elevated levels
in the second half of fiscal 1990.
   The company also told analysts that it expects combined
second half domestic and international growth rates to be a
modest 7% to 10%. Indeed, despite the second-quarter showing,
Apple's stock closed unchanged at $43.25 a share yesterday on
volume of 1.7 million shares in national over-the-counter
trading.
   Apple said its results were greatly aided by record
international sales, which totaled 47% of all sales for the
quarter, which also set a record. Apple attributed the
increase to aggressive overseas marketing efforts coupled
with "the relatively higher growth rates the industry is
experiencing in markets outside the United States."
   Indeed, Apple said that while it remains "cautious" about
growth in the U.S. computer industry in coming quarters, "we
are optimistic regarding the level of international demand."
   Apple said profit also received a boost from improved
margins on its computer products, stemming from lower parts
costs and a more effective program of managing operating
expenses.
   The company added that results were aided by brisk sales
of upgraded models of its mid- and high-end Macintosh
computer introduced last year. The machines, notably the
Macintosh FE 30, 2ci and 2cx, retail between about $3,800 to
$8,600 depending upon the configuration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
