   Business Brief -- Signal Apparel Co.:
   Walsh Greenwood Will Buy
   51% Holding From Trusts
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16
</SO>
<CO>
   SIA WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Signal Apparel Co. said Walsh, Greenwood &amp; Co. agreed to
buy as much as a 51% stake from trusts for the benefit of
George B. Clairmont, a director and former chairman of the
apparel company.
   Signal Apparel, Chattanooga, Tenn., said the New York
limited partnership agreed to buy about 25% of the Class A
common and 6% of the cumulative convertible preferred shares
from the trusts. Walsh Greenwood also has a two-year option
to buy 60% of the Class B common held by the trusts, the
company said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The transaction's value wasn't disclosed. The company
said, however, that Walsh Greenwood will pay $4.50 for each
Class A share, $18 apiece for the preferred, and $6.50 for
each Class B share.
   Signal said that subject to certain conditions, the
transaction is expected to close in 10 days.
   It said upon closing of the transaction, Roger Holland,
former president and chief executive officer of Champion
Products Inc., would be named president and chief executive
officer, succeeding Robert B. Colbert Jr., who will either
remain chairman or become vice chairman.
