900419-0009.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology:
   Two Teams
   Place Genes
   Into Corn
   ----
   By Jerry E. Bishop
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   MTC SEEDB
</CO>
<IN>
MEDICAL AND BIOTECHNOLOGY (MTC)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<GV>
AGRICULTURE DEPARTMENT (AGD)
</GV>
<LP>
   Two biotechnology teams announced they have successfully
inserted foreign genes into corn plants, a major goal of
agricultural biotechnology.
   DeKalb Genetics Corp., a commercial seed producer, and a
joint U.S. Department of Agriculture-Monsanto Co. team both
announced they had successfully produced fertile, genetically
altered corn plants capable of passing their new genes on to
succeeding generations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The feat opens the way to making corn, the nation's
biggest crop, resistant to disease, drought and herbicides,
as well as to increasing its nutritional value.
   A similar bioengineering claim was made in January by
BioTechnica International Inc. Unlike DeKalb and the
USDA-Monsanto team, however, BioTechnica has declined to say
what genes it inserted into corn plants and what technique it
used.
   Getting new genes into corn also has implications for
other key grain crops such as wheat and rice. Until now,
inserting new genes into plants has been successful only in a
class of plants known as "dicots," those that produce two
leaf-like growths called cotyledons when their seeds first
sprout. Tomatoes, tobacco and rapeseed are among the dicots
that have been successfully engineered genetically.
   Corn, as well as wheat, rice and other cereals, is among
the "monocots" that produce only a single cotyledon on
sprouting and that have defied attempts at genetic
engineering. While scientists have been able to get new genes
into monocot plants, the plants previously have ended up
sterile and unable to pass the new genes on in their seed.
   DeKalb said its scientists had used a "gene gun" to fire
microscopic pellets into test-tube cultured cells of the corn
plant. The pellets were coated with a gene that produces a
resistance to the herbicide bialaphos. Cells that
incorporated the new gene were identified by the fact that
they survived treatment with bialaphos. The genetically
altered cells were then grown into full-sized corn plants
that, in turn, produced seed resistant to the herbicide.
   The bialaphos-resistance gene was used only because it
served as a "marker," enabling the scientists to track the
gene. The gene is of little economic importance in the U.S.,
where bialaphos isn't used, though it's used in Europe,
according to Thomas Rice, a DeKalb scientist.
   The DeKalb research was carried out at laboratories in
Groton, Conn., leased from Pfizer Inc. Earlier this year,
DeKalb bought out Pfizer's 30% equity interest in what had
been a joint venture, DeKalb-Pfizer Genetics.
   The USDA-Monsanto announcement said USDA scientists at
laboratories in Albany, Calif., had used a similar "gene gun"
to fire new genes into corn-cell cultures developed at
Monsanto's laboratories in St. Louis. The scientists inserted
two "marker" genes into the corn cells: one gene that allowed
the cells to grow in the presence of an inhibitor; and a
second gene, taken from fireflies, that causes the cells
incorporating the gene to glow under a special low-light
detector.
   The cells that incorporated the two genes were grown to
mature plants that were then pollinated. The resulting seeds
were planted in a greenhouse where a crop of seedlings is now
growing. The light-detector has found that about half the
seedlings have the firefly gene.
   The feats are a major technological advance, but
scientists cautioned it may be several years before farmers
will have genetically altered seed to plant. Not only must
scientists get the right genes into corn, but they have to
make sure the genetic alteration doesn't affect the yield and
other valuable attributes of the plant. It will take several
seasons of field-testing to produce useful genetically
engineered hybrid corn seed, Mr. Rice cautioned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900419-0008
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900419-0008.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Kenny Learns
   About Show Biz
   Of Another Kind
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<LP>
   Kenny Rogers, a mellow sort of fellow, this week finds
himself tangled in a decidedly unmellow dispute. Rolling
Stone magazine has named the bearded balladeer in its "Hall
of Shame" hit list of international environmental sinners.
The magazine also included the Journal's editorial page on
its roster -- a more predictable choice. But we were
surprised to find ourselves in such affable company. Rolling
Stone describes Mr. Rogers as an "ardent apologist for the
Los Angeles-based Summit Cement Company, which has sought to
dump toxic wastes from the U.S. mainland on Grand Bahama
Island." Rolling Stone says Mr. Rogers flew the Bahamian
health minister to Florida to help Summit.
   Wrong, says Kenny. He did fly ministers to Florida, but it
was because he was thinking of buying a hotel from the
Bahamian government. The singer is indeed a friend of
Summit's president, Finn Moller. But the only "help" Mr.
Rogers gave Mr. Moller was to aid him in investigating the
environmental safety of a plant Summit thought of buying on
Grand Bahama. In fact, charges Mr. Rogers, Rolling Stone only
heard about the matter because his own investigation was so
large.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Rogers is on a 70-city concert tour with Dolly Parton.
But during a break he spoke with Amity Shlaes of the
editorial page by phone from his farm in Athens, Ga.
Excerpts:
                                                                                                       

   What did you feel when you saw your name in Rolling Stone?
   This kind of thing really takes the wind out of your
sails. It makes you wonder why you do things in life.
                                                                                                       

   What really hap pened with the ce ment plant in the
Bahamas?
   At the start I was interested in re searching whether the
plant would be safe because I was thinking of investing {in
the Bahamas} myself. What I found was there are already 15
cement plants of this type operating legally in the United
States. They use hazardous waste not toxic waste {as Rolling
Stone asserts}. Every one of those {plants} wrote me positive
letters. Then I call Greenpeace in San Francisco. I say to
them as a joke: "I know that you guys are the shark in this
situation" -- meaning that they are the hardcore people who
can answer. The guy says "off the record, I'm sure the plant
is safe but I still can't approve."
                                                                                                       

   What did he mean?
   It appears some people would rather win than be right.
                                                                                                       

   Why is it OK to build a plant that uses hazardous waste at
all?
   I am a strange kind of guy. In the world there are very
few things that are black and white. In this case the
hazardous waste, a petroleum byproduct, is used to make a
product that is safe. {In general} something needs to be done
with hazardous waste. Until we find an alternative source,
what do you do with that waste? This seemed a good use.
                                                                                                       

   Why do you think Greenpeace and Rolling Stone are picking
on you?
   They jumped on the bandwagon and used me because I get
more press than anybody else.
                                                                                                       

   What does Dolly think?
   She has never mentioned it. We usually run into each other
only on stage.
                                                                                                       

   Are you doing anything for Earth Day?
   In my business you learn early that you have to pick your
causes. Mine are world hunger and the homeless. Every year I
host a weekend here at my farm to raise money for the
homeless.
                                                                                                       

   Has environmentalism gone too far in America?
   I have never been a person who admires extremists in any
field.
                                                                                                       

   Robert Vare, the Rolling Stone editor who handled the
"Hall of Shame" section, says the magazine stands by its
report. Kenny Rogers never did buy the hotel on the Bahamas.
Finn Moller, the man who wanted to buy the cement plant, says
environmentalist roadblocks forced him to give up the
project, which would have brought 400 jobs to the
underemployed islands.
   As someone once sang: You've got to know when to hold 'em,
know when to fold 'em.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900419-0007
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900419-0007.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   U.S. Persuades Allied-Signal to End
   Unfair Trade Complaint Against Japan
   ---
   By John T. Norman and Eduardo Lachica
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<CO>
   ALD JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The U.S. persuaded Allied-Signal Inc. to
withdraw a trade complaint against Japan, at least
temporarily, while the two countries seek to negotiate a
solution.
   At issue are complaints by the U.S. company that Japan
restricts imports of amorphous metals, a high-technology
product used in electric-power transmission equipment. The
Bush administration's decision to negotiate the issue with
Tokyo, rather than launch a formal trade investigation that
could lead to retaliation, signals the administration's
intent to reduce the heat of the current trade dialogue with
Japan. U.S. officials said the Bush administration doesn't
want to give Japan a black eye so soon after that country
agreed to trade concessions in so-called structural
impediments talks with the U.S.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Although Carla Hills, the U.S. trade representative, said
nothing about other U.S. trade complaints awaiting action,
the tone of her announcement suggested that the White House
is considering nonconfrontational solutions for them, as
well. At the end of this month, Mrs. Hills has to determine
whether to list Japan as an unfair trading partner under the
"Super 301" provision of the 1988 trade act.
   Mrs. Hills said that if bilateral negotiations aren't
successful in resolving the amorphous metals dispute within
150 days, the U.S. will invite Allied-Signal to resubmit its
petition for prompt action.
   In Morris Township, N.J., Edward L. Hennessy Jr.,
Allied-Signal's chairman and chief executive officer, said
the company will cooperate with Mrs. Hills. "The recently
announced progress in the trade talks between the U.S. and
Japan holds out the promise that trade issues between the two
nations can be resolved in a more businesslike and less
confrontational manner," he said. "We hope that
Allied-Signal's case will demonstrate that this process
works."
   Allied-Signal filed the trade complaint March 5, alleging
that Japan "has engaged in practices aimed at excluding sales
of U.S. amorphous metals." The U.S. company also charged that
Tokyo has blocked attempts to license technology to Japanese
companies. Mrs. Hills was required under the 1988 trade act
to accept or reject the complaint by today.
   Mrs. Hills has used similar tactics to deal with trade
complaints from other U.S. industries. For example, this past
summer the Shipbuilders Council of America, an industry
group, withdrew a trade complaint about government subsidies
to commercial shipbuilders in South Korea, Japan, West
Germany and Norway after Mrs. Hills promised that the U.S.
would seek to negotiate a broad international agreement to
restrict and eventually eliminate such subsidies.
   The U.S. negotiations with South Korea and member
countries of the Paris-based Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development on shipyard subsidies haven't
been concluded, although U.S. officials say they are making
progress and the talks should be completed next month.
   In its petition, Allied-Signal charged that Japanese
government agencies and businesses worked in concert to keep
the company's amorphous metals out of the Japanese market
while domestic producers tried to develop an equivalent
product. Amorphous metals are used primarily to improve the
efficiency of electrical transmission and have a world market
estimated at about $1 billion a year.
   Mrs. Hills's action drew a cautious reaction from
Congress. Rep. Helen Bentley (R., Md.) said the move was a
"Solomon-like decision." But Sen. John Danforth (R., Mo.)
warned that the administration could be "falling into a
pattern of sidestepping U.S. trade law." He stressed that the
"bottom line has to be results in the form of exports for a
U.S. firm that is being shut out by Japan."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
