<HL>
   GF Corp., Unit Seek
   Creditor Protection
   Of Bankruptcy Code
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16
</SO>
<CO>
   GFB
</CO>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio -- GF Corp. said it and its wholly owned
GF Furniture Systems Inc. subsidiary have filed for
protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal
Bankruptcy Code.
   The maker of office furniture also said its
furniture-systems unit has agreed in principle to sell
substantially all of its assets, including manufacturing
facilities, trademarks and patents, to a private holding
company. The holding company will be formed by Cyrus Tang,
the owner of Tang Industries of Chicago, a $700 million
steel-service concern.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   GF has had trouble obtaining sufficient financing for
general working capital and to cover the closing costs of its
88-year-old Youngstown manufacturing plant. That plant had
been posting losses of between $9 million and $10 million a
year, because it wasn't producing enough to cover operating
costs.
   In its filing, the company listed total assets of $44
million and total liabilities of $57 million, excluding
certain health care and lease liabilities, which are listed
off the company's balance sheet.
   GF said the agreement to sell the furniture-systems assets
calls for the Tang group to provide new capital and pay off
about $22 million of bank debt, and make additional payments
to GF Furniture Systems during the next six years based on
earnings from furniture operations. The agreement doesn't
cover the unit's trade debt, liability for shutdown costs, or
health and other labor contract obligations.
   GF said its directors have approved the immediate
conversion of GF's Class B common shares outstanding into an
equal number of common shares. The company said the Class B
shares had superior voting power; otherwise, they were
identical to regular common.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900419-0002
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900419-0002.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Who's News:
   Savin Marketing Chief
   Merriman Is Named
   To President's Post
</HL>
<DATE>
04/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   SVB WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
</IN>
<LP>
   STAMFORD, Conn. -- Savin Corp. said its top marketing
executive, Brian Merriman, was named president, succeeding
William T. Smith, who will become vice chairman and remain
chief operating officer.
   The appointments are effective May 16.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The 52-year-old Mr. Merriman is executive vice president,
sales and marketing, at the marketer of copiers and facsimile
equipment, a post once held by Mr. Smith, 48.
   Savin credited Mr. Merriman with fostering closer ties
between the parent's sales organization and both independent
and company-owned sales offices. The executive vice
president's position will remain vacant for now, a
spokeswoman said.
   Separately, Savin declared a dividend on its Series A
preferred shares, payable May 1 to stock of record April 27.
   A proposal that shareholders approved last month allowed
Savin to pay the Series A dividend and arrearages with common
shares. Thus, Savin will issue 415,000 common shares to pay
the current dividend and about 7.5 million additional shares
to eliminate arrearages since November 1985. This means each
Series A share will receive about 1.6 common shares as a
current dividend plus 28.5 shares to cure the arrearages.
   Savin has 132 million common shares and 263,709 Series A
shares outstanding.
   At a special meeting of shareholders scheduled for
tomorrow, Savin will announce the results of further
balloting on four of eight proposals that didn't pass
previously. With the proposals, the company is asking holders
for more flexibility to pay dividends and for the right to
award certain options.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Savin shares closed at 25 cents, unchanged.
</TEXT>
